@Serdar G√∂kay - I'm defending Ignition Historian here but from what I have heard from your needs, I would only use it if you are going to use Ignition in your architecture either way.

Kepware and Timebase is probably where I would start. 

Run it for a short pilot and see if it works, if not - I would investigate more options. Like Ignition, Canary, PI, or building your own (depending on internal capabilities) with QuestDB, Timescale, or InfluxDB.

HighByte has a lot of capabilities for processing text files. It can read/browse directories for changes, open files, and transform/model the contents. There are a few options to integrate with Flow.

If you have a general file directory with a lot of different publishing patterns to accommodate, a "pull" approach might make sense. You could build a Pipeline to expose the directory and files as an API. The Pipeline could be setup to keep track of what has been successful processed from the text file(s). Flow would connect using its Cloud/WebService client interface to HighByte's REST Data Server. You could build a custom endpoint for the client. Flow also has an MQTT Client. A HighByte Pipeline could convert the events from the text file into to MQTT publishes for Flow to subscribe to.

@Zach E, did I miss any options? I covered "pull" scenarios. Is there a "push" option? Does Flow have an ingestion endpoint Intelligence Hub could publish to?
